'''Toni Michele Braxton''' (born October 7, 1967<ref name=":0" />) is an American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer. She has sold over 70 million records worldwide and is one of the best-selling female artists in history. Braxton has won seven [[Grammy Awards]], nine [[Billboard Music Awards]], seven [[American Music Awards]], and numerous other accolades. In 2011, Braxton was inducted into the [[Georgia Music Hall of Fame]]. In 2017 she was honored with the Legend Award at the [[2017 Soul Train Music Awards|Soul Train Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Anthony Anderson presents the Legend Award to Toni Braxton onstage at...|url=https://www.gettyimages.ch/detail/nachrichtenfoto/anthony-anderson-presents-the-legend-award-to-toni-nachrichtenfoto/870716248|access-date=December 1, 2020|website=Getty Images|language=it}}</ref>

In the late 1980s, Braxton began performing with her sisters in a music group known as [[The Braxtons]]; the group was signed to [[Arista Records]]. After attracting the attention of producers [[Antonio "L.A." Reid]] and [[Kenneth "Babyface" Edmonds]] and being signed to [[LaFace Records]], Braxton released her [[Toni Braxton (album)|self-titled debut studio album]] in 1993. The album reached number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and sold 10 million copies worldwide. In addition, the singles "[[Another Sad Love Song]]" and "[[Breathe Again]]" became international successes. The album brought Braxton three [[Grammy Awards]], including the Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].

Braxton experienced continued success with the albums ''[[Secrets (Toni Braxton album)|Secrets]]'' (1996), which included the U.S. #1 hit singles "[[You're Makin' Me High]]/[[Let It Flow (song)|Let It Flow]]" and "[[Un-Break My Heart]]"; and ''[[The Heat (Toni Braxton album)|The Heat]]'' (2000), which opened at #2 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and included the U.S. #2 hit single "[[He Wasn't Man Enough]]". Braxton's subsequent studio albums, ''[[More Than a Woman (album)|More Than a Woman]]'' (2002), ''[[Libra (Toni Braxton album)|Libra]]'' (2005) and ''[[Pulse (Toni Braxton album)|Pulse]]'' (2010), were released amid contractual disputes and health issues. In 2014, Braxton and longtime collaborator [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] released a duet album entitled ''[[Love, Marriage & Divorce]]'' that earned the duo a [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album]] in 2015. Further label changes saw the release of ''[[Sex & Cigarettes]]'' (2018) under [[Def Jam]]/[[Universal Music|Universal]] and ''[[Spell My Name]]'' (2020) under [[Island Records|Island]].

Braxton is also a television executive producer and personality. She competed in the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of the reality competition series ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''. She has executive produced and starred in ''[[Braxton Family Values]]'', a reality television series that has aired on [[We TV]] since 2011. Braxton was also an executive producer of  ''[[Tamar & Vince]]'', a spinoff reality TV series starring her younger sister, Tamar.

==Early life==
Toni Michele Braxton was born in [[Severn, Maryland]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ollison|first1=Rashod D.|title=Toni Braxton's back, with a pretty 'Please'|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2005-09-25/news/0509270511_1_toni-braxton-libra-albums|access-date=November 15, 2015|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=September 25, 2005}}</ref> on October 7, 1967.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/07/toni-braxton-celebrates-46th-birthday-_n_1945819.html|title=PHOTOS: Toni Blows Out The Candles For Her 46th Birthday|date=October 7, 2012|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> Her father, Michael Conrad Braxton Sr., was a [[Methodist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adherents.com/largecom/fam_meth.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010304033809/http://www.adherents.com/largecom/fam_meth.html|url-status=usurped|archive-date=March 4, 2001|title=Famous Methodists|website=Adherents.com|access-date=November 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Jet|journal = Jet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I7sDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA21|access-date=December 2, 2013|date=June 20, 1994|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|page=21|issn=0021-5996}}</ref> [[clergyman]] and power company worker, and her mother, Evelyn Jackson, a native of [[South Carolina]], was a former opera singer and cosmetologist, as well as a pastor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dougherty|first=Steve|title=Greener Pastures|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20132603,00.html|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Braxton Family Values – Evelyn Braxton|url=http://www.wetv.com/shows/braxton-family-values/cast/evelyn-braxton|website=Wetv.com|access-date=December 2, 2013}}</ref> Braxton's maternal grandfather was also a pastor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ney|first=Angela Winter|title=Award-winning pastor reaches out to teen-agers|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-02-06/news/1994037080_1_toni-braxton-inside-the-church-award|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=February 6, 1994}}</ref>

Braxton is the eldest of six siblings.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rizzo|first1=Monica|title=Toni Braxton: Still Dancing|journal=People|date=October 27, 2008|volume=70|issue=17|url= http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20238199,00.html|access-date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> She has a younger brother Michael Jr. (born 1968) and four younger sisters [[Traci Braxton|Traci Renee]] (1971 - 2022), [[Towanda Braxton|Towanda Chloe]] (born 1973), [[Trina Braxton|Trina Evette]] (born 1974), and [[Tamar Braxton|Tamar Estine]] (born 1977). They were raised in a strict religious household,<ref name="psu">{{cite web|url=http://www.premiumseatsusa.com/concert/Toni-Braxton|title=Toni Braxton Tickets|access-date=December 18, 2006|work=Premium Seats USA}}</ref> and Braxton's first performing experience was singing in her church choir.<ref name="psu"/>

Braxton attended [[Bowie State University]] to obtain a teaching degree,<ref>{{Cite news|first=Joy Bennett|last=Kinnon|title=The Rise and Fall and Rise of Toni Braxton|work=Ebony|date=December 2000}}</ref> but decided to sing professionally after she was discovered by William E. Pettaway Jr., who reportedly heard her singing to herself while pumping gas.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Morgan|last=Joan|title=Fully Exposed|work=Vibe|date=December 2002|quote=One day in 1990, songwriter Bill Pettaway heard Toni singing to herself at an Annapolis gas station, liked what he heard, and got her an audition with L.A.}}</ref>

On her appearance May 24, 2014 broadcast of [[NPR]]'s ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'', she stated that she was not singing to herself at the gas station. Pettaway, working as an attendant at the [[Annapolis]] service station where she was refueling, recognized her from local performances and introduced himself, saying he wanted to produce her. Although skeptical, Braxton decided to, in her words, "take a chance" and accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/programs/wait-wait-dont-tell-me/315248388/wait-wait-dont-tell-me-for-may-24-2014|title=Wait, Wait, Don't Tell Me! For May 24, 2014|website=Npr.org|access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref>

==Career==
===1989–1995: The Braxtons, ''Toni Braxton'' and breakthrough===
{{Main|The Braxtons}}
Braxton and her four sisters Traci, Towanda, Trina, and Tamar began performing as [[The Braxtons]] in the late 1980s and were signed to [[Arista Records]] in 1989. Their first single, "[[Good Life (The Braxtons song)|Good Life]]", was released in 1990.<ref name="vibe">{{cite web |url = http://www.vibe.com/music/search/artist.html?id=UCAgICAzNzU3Ng |title = Toni Braxton |access-date = December 18, 2006 |work = VIBE.com |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071112190035/http://www.vibe.com/music/search/artist.html?id=UCAgICAzNzU3Ng |archive-date = November 12, 2007 }}</ref> Though the song was not successful, it attracted the attention of record executive [[Antonio "L.A." Reid]] and record producer [[Kenneth "Babyface" Edmonds]].<ref name="vibe"/> Reid and Babyface recruited her to record a demo of "[[Love Shoulda Brought You Home]]", a song that they had written for Anita Baker for the soundtrack of [[Eddie Murphy]]'s film, ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]''. Baker, who was pregnant at the time, did not record the song but suggested that Braxton record it.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://uk.askmen.com/women/singer/8c_toni_braxton.html |title = Toni Braxton |access-date = December 18, 2006 |work = AskMen |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181638/http://uk.askmen.com/women/singer/8c_toni_braxton.html |archive-date = September 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Her recording was later included on the soundtrack along with "[[Give U My Heart]]", a duet by Braxton and Babyface. Braxton, meanwhile, was signed to Reid and Edmonds' Arista-distributed imprint, [[LaFace Records]], and immediately began recording her solo debut album.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

In July 1993, LaFace released Braxton's [[Toni Braxton (album)|self-titled debut album]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Toni-Braxton/dp/B0000013G5|title=''Toni Braxton'': Music: Toni Braxton|access-date=December 18, 2006|website=Amazon.com|year=1993 }}</ref> Primarily produced by Reid, [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], and [[Daryl Simmons]], it peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and entered the top ten of the albums chart in Australia, Canada, Germany, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?pid=30331&aid=146011|title=Discography&nbsp;– Toni Braxton – ''Toni Braxton''|access-date=December 18, 2006|website=Billboard.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929141413/http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?pid=30331&aid=146011|archive-date=September 29, 2007}}</ref> The first single, "[[Another Sad Love Song]]", peaked at number seven and number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks|R&B Singles]] charts respectively.<ref name="billboard singles">{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.vnuArtistId=30331&model.vnuAlbumId=146011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929211922/http://billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.vnuArtistId=30331&model.vnuAlbumId=146011|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 29, 2007|title=Artist Chart History&nbsp;– Toni Braxton|access-date=December 18, 2006|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> The album's second single, "[[Breathe Again]]", peaked in the top five of both the Hot 100 and R&B singles charts<ref name="billboard singles"/> and no 2 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com|title=UK Top 40 Chart Archive, British Singles & Album Charts|website=Everyhit.com|date=March 16, 2000|access-date=January 16, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702234638/http://www.everyhit.com/|archive-date=July 2, 2007}}</ref> More singles from ''Toni Braxton'' were released in 1994, including "[[You Mean the World to Me (Toni Braxton song)|You Mean the World to Me]]", "[[Seven Whole Days]]", and "[[I Belong to You/How Many Ways]]".<ref name="billboard singles"/>

Braxton's debut album won her several awards, including three [[Grammy Award]]s (for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] and two consecutive awards for [[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]] in 1994 and 1995).<ref name="YTV">{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/toni-braxton/contributor/38261/awards|title=Toni Braxton|access-date=December 26, 2006|work=Yahoo! TV|date=March 14, 2003}}</ref> She won two [[American Music Award]]s (for Favorite Soul/R&B New Artist and Favorite New Adult Contemporary Artist)<ref name="YTV"/> in 1994 and another one in 1995 (for Favorite Soul/R&B Album).<ref name="YTV"/> ''Toni Braxton'' was certified 8× platinum in USA and has sales of over 10 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gp/bestsellers/topalbums.asp|title=Gold&Platinum: Top 100 albums|access-date=December 18, 2006|work=RIAA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214122646/http://www.riaa.com/gp/bestsellers/topalbums.asp|archive-date=December 14, 2006}}</ref><ref name="books.google.com">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ArUDAAAAMBAJ&q=toni+braxton+sold&pg=PA56|title=Jet&nbsp;– Google Livros|date=July 17, 2000|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|access-date=November 12, 2010}}</ref>

===1996–1999: ''Secrets'' and financial issues===
In June 1996, Braxton released her second album ''[[Secrets (Toni Braxton album)|Secrets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000013GH|title=''Secrets'': Music: Toni Braxton|access-date=December 18, 2006|website=Amazon.com}}</ref> Motivated "to include a little bit of everything,"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-b/tonibraxton_main.htm|title=Toni Braxton|access-date=December 18, 2006|work=Rock on the Net}}</ref> Braxton reteamed with Babyface, but also worked with [[R. Kelly]], [[Tony Rich]], and [[David Foster]] on the album, which she co-produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,230175,00.html?src=search#credits|title=Toni Braxton: ''Secrets'' |access-date=December 18, 2006|work=ArtistDirect}}</ref> A major success, it peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 and reached the top ten on most international charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?JSESSIONID=FHJ2kFF9nFq0gg5KtPxXY8nGJ2sqxnQLL1brcY1T26XLrc1Q1lcF!-1562377538&pid=30331&aid=185866|title=Discography&nbsp;– Toni Braxton – ''Secrets''|access-date=December 18, 2006|website=Billboard.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929141203/http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?JSESSIONID=FHJ2kFF9nFq0gg5KtPxXY8nGJ2sqxnQLL1brcY1T26XLrc1Q1lcF%21-1562377538&pid=30331&aid=185866|archive-date=September 29, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> After 92 weeks in the charts, ''Secrets'' was certified 8× platinum, becoming Braxton's second straight 8 million-seller. Internationally, ''Secrets'' sold more than 15 million copies, further cementing Braxton's superstar status.<ref name="books.google.com" /> The album's first single, "[[You're Makin' Me High]]", marked Braxton's first number-one hit on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref name="billboard singles"/> while follow-up "[[Un-Break My Heart]]", a ballad written and composed by [[Diane Warren]], became the biggest hit of Braxton's career yet. It spent eleven consecutive weeks at number one on the Hot 100 and enjoyed worldwide top five success.<ref name="vibe"/><ref name="mfc">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicfanclubs.org/tonibraxton/timeline.htm|title=Toni Braxton|access-date=December 26, 2006|work=Music Fan Clubs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com|title=UK Top 40 Chart Archive, British Singles & Album Charts|website=Everyhit.com|date=March 16, 2000|access-date=February 1, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702234638/http://www.everyhit.com/|archive-date=July 2, 2007}}</ref>

As a result, Braxton topped several of ''Billboard''{{'}}s year-end charts,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+Hot+100&g=Year-end+Singles&year=1997 |title=Year End Charts&nbsp;– Year-end Singles&nbsp;– The Billboard Hot 100 |access-date=December 26, 2006 |website=Billboard.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061224112647/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+Hot+100&g=Year-end+Singles&year=1997 |archive-date=December 24, 2006 }}</ref> and won two Grammy Awards; one for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]]<ref name="YTV" /> for "Un-Break My Heart" and Best Female R&B Vocal Performance for "You're Makin' Me High" as well as two [[American Music Award]]s for Favorite Female Soul/R&B Artist and Favorite Soul/R&B Album.<ref name="YTV" /> Still waiting on her financial rewards, Braxton eventually launched an unsuccessful lawsuit against Arista and LaFace Records. Soon after, she filed for chapter 7 bankruptcy. Public reaction to these events was very harsh, having been expressed most clearly in an interview on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].''<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ftLjr4CQcrQ |title = "She was so frickin' mean to me": Toni Braxton's Original Full Interview with Oprah (1998) |publisher = YouTube |date = March 29, 2013 |access-date = July 8, 2015 }}</ref>

Braxton has appeared in two [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] shows: She made her Broadway debut as Belle in ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' beginning September 9, 1998 when she replaced Kim Huber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40798-Braxton-Taylor-Barbour-Beast-to-Be-Unveiled-Sept-9-New-Menken-Song-to-Follow |title=Braxton-Taylor-Barbour Beast to Be Unveiled Sept. 9; New Menken Song to Follow |access-date=June 27, 2010 |work=playbill |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016144402/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40798-Braxton-Taylor-Barbour-Beast-to-Be-Unveiled-Sept-9-New-Menken-Song-to-Follow |archive-date=October 16, 2012 }}</ref> During her run in the show [[Alan Menken]] wrote and composed a new song for the musical, titled "A Change in Me", which he specially wrote and composed for Braxton, and was still being used in the musical as of late July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41311-Toni-Braxton-Premieres-Beauty-s-New-Song-Oct-7-On-Rosie |title=Toni Braxton Premieres Beauty's New Song, Oct. 7 On 'Rosie' |website=Playbill.com |access-date=January 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016144507/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41311-Toni-Braxton-Premieres-Beauty-s-New-Song-Oct-7-On-Rosie |archive-date=October 16, 2012 }}</ref> She left the production on February 28, 1999, and was succeeded by [[Andrea McArdle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/43273-Bways-Beauty-Turns-2000-Sat-Matinee-Jan-30-McArdle-Arrives-March-3 |title=Bway's Beauty Turns 2,000 Sat. Matinee Jan. 30; McArdle Arrives March 3 |website=Playbill.com |access-date=January 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016144741/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/43273-Bways-Beauty-Turns-2000-Sat-Matinee-Jan-30-McArdle-Arrives-March-3 |archive-date=October 16, 2012 }}</ref> Her role in ''Beauty and the Beast'' marked the first (and only) time a black woman commanded the leading role of Belle on Broadway. (In the UK, [[Michelle Gayle]] played the role in the West End.) It also marked the first time a black woman would star in a Disney musical on Broadway. In 1999, the lawsuit against LaFace Records was settled and Braxton was given back all her possessions, giving her time to record ''The Heat'', her first album in four years.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.lifetimetv.com/shows/ip/portraits/0223/0223_bio.html |title = Toni Braxton |access-date = December 18, 2006 |work = Lifetime's intimate portrait |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051205012041/http://www.lifetimetv.com/shows/ip/portraits/0223/0223_bio.html |archive-date = December 5, 2005 }}</ref>

===2000–2002: ''The Heat'', ''More Than a Woman'', and acting debut===
After her three-year-long dispute with LaFace and Arista had been settled, Braxton signed a new $20 million contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toni Braxton Settles With LaFace Records, Starts Work On Album |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1426556/toni-braxton-settles-with-laface-records-starts-work-on-album/|website=mtv.com|date=January 13, 1999|access-date=May 31, 2020}}</ref> In April 2000, her third studio album, ''[[The Heat (Toni Braxton album)|The Heat]]'' was released. Braxton took a more hands-on approach, co-writing and co-producing a handful of the tracks which saw her adapting a more [[urban contemporary|urban]] sound. It opened at number two on the US ''Billboard'' 200 with 199,000 copies sold in its first week, eventually going double platinum in the United States, while selling over 4 million copies worldwide.<ref name="books.google.com"/><ref name=vibe2002>{{cite book|title=Vibe Magazine|date=December 2002|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_uyUEAAAAMBAJ|quote=THE HEAT.|publisher=[[Internet Archive]]|access-date=May 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht692|title=Previous Album Sales Chart|publisher=HITS Daily Double|access-date=November 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908231013/http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht692|archive-date=September 8, 2012}}</ref>  Additionally, the album was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album|Best R&B Album]] at the [[43rd Grammy Awards|2001 Grammy Awards]], while uptempo lead single "[[He Wasn't Man Enough]]", a worldwide top ten hit, won for [[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]] and was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]].<ref name=rockonthenet>{{cite web|title=Rock on the Net: Toni Braxton|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-b/tonibraxton_main.htm|work=Rock on the Net|access-date=May 24, 2014}}</ref>

In 2001, Braxton made her movie acting debut in director [[Doug McHenry]]'s comedy film ''[[Kingdom Come (2001 film)|Kingdom Come]]'' opposite an ensemble also starring [[LL Cool J]], [[Jada Pinkett Smith]], and [[Whoopi Goldberg]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0246002|title=Kingdom Come|access-date=December 19, 2006|website=IMDb.com|date=April 11, 2001}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=November 2019}} A modest box-office success, it grossed $23.4 million worldwide.<ref>{{Mojo title|kingdomcome}}</ref> The same year, Braxton recorded and released the [[Christmas album]] ''[[Snowflakes (album)|Snowflakes]]'' which consisted [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]–led original songs co-penned with Keri Lewis and Babyface as well as several remixes and cover versions of [[Christmas music#Popular Christmas songs|Christmas standards]] and [[Christmas carol|carol]]s. It received a mixed reception by critics, many of whom compared its nature to Braxton's other work but found the stylized production and original material too contemporary to conjure images of [[Christmas]], and failed to reach the upper half of the ''Billboard'' 200, eventually going gold in the United States.

In 2002, while gearing up for the release of her fourth studio album, Braxton discovered she was pregnant with her second child. Knowing that she would be unable to promote the album properly, she unsuccessfully lobbied [[Arista Records]] to get the label to postpone its release until after she was to give birth. In November 2002,  ''[[More Than a Woman (album)|More Than a Woman]]'' was released. Opening to an instant commercial disappointment, the album peaked at number 13 on the US ''Billboard'' 200, but was less successful internationally. The first single "[[Hit the Freeway]]" failed to impact, resulting in lackluster sales in general and the release of no further singles. ''More Than a Woman'' was eventually certified gold in the United States and sold more than 800,000 copies worldwide.<ref name="musicmp3.ru">{{cite web |url = http://musicmp3.ru/artist_toni-braxton.html |title = Toni Braxton mp3 music download |publisher = MusicMp3.Ru |access-date = November 12, 2010 }}</ref>

=== 2003–2007: ''Libra'' and Las Vegas residency===
In April 2003, Braxton abruptly left Arista Records, having been there for 14 years, and immediately signed with [[Blackground Records]], headed by [[Barry Hankerson]], her manager at the time. She then starred in ''[[Aida (musical)|Aida]]'' as Aida beginning June 30, 2003 when she replaced actress [[Simone (actress)|Simone]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12037443 |title = Toni Braxton Set To Return To Broadway |access-date = December 19, 2006 |work = Yahoo! Music |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612053315/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12037443 |archive-date = June 12, 2007 }}</ref> until she left the cast on November 16, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82297-Its-Destiny-RB-Singer-Michelle-Williams-to-Replace-Toni-Braxton-in-Aida |title=It's Destiny: R&B Singer Michelle Williams to Replace Toni Braxton in Aida |website=Playbill.com |first=Andrew|last= Gans|date= October 22, 2003|access-date=January 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016144804/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82297-Its-Destiny-RB-Singer-Michelle-Williams-to-Replace-Toni-Braxton-in-Aida |archive-date=October 16, 2012 }}</ref> In April 2005, Braxton's new label, Blackground/Universal, released "[[Please (Toni Braxton song)|Please]]", the first single from her fifth album, ''[[Libra (Toni Braxton album)|Libra]]''. The album was originally planned for a June release, but it was pushed back several times and was finally issued on September 27. ''Libra'' peaked at number four on the US ''Billboard'' 200, selling 114,593 copies in the first week, and peaked at number two on the Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums. The album was certified gold in late 2005 and has since sold 679,000 copies worldwide.<ref name="musicmp3.ru" />

[[File:Flamingo (2597820752).jpg|thumb|left|[[Flamingo Las Vegas]] promoting headliner Braxton and her ''[[Toni Braxton: Revealed]]'' show in 2006]] In May 2005, Braxton made an appearance on the season finale of ''[[American Idol (season 5)|American Idol 5]]'', where she performed [[Elvis Presley]]'s "[[In the Ghetto]]" with soon-to-be winner [[Taylor Hicks]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1532468/20060524/hicks__taylor.jhtml |title = Soul Patrol Rides On: Taylor Hicks Wins 'American Idol' |access-date = December 27, 2006 |work = MTV News |date = May 25, 2006 }}</ref> A month later, "[[The Time of Our Lives (Il Divo and Toni Braxton song)|The Time of Our Lives]]", a duet with classical crossover vocal group [[Il Divo]], was released as a single, serving as the official [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] anthem. Braxton performed the song, which entered the top ten in Switzerland, at the opening ceremony in [[Berlin]] on June 9, 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16862049&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=fiona--divo--name_page.html |title = Fiona: divo |access-date = December 18, 2006 |work = Mirror.co.uk }}</ref> In August 2006, Braxton replaced singer [[Wayne Newton]] as the [[Flamingo Las Vegas]]'s new headlining act.<ref>{{cite news |title = Toni Braxton to be headliner at Flamingo Las Vegas to 2007 |url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/hotels/2006-05-19-braxtons-back_x.htm |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[USA Today]] |date = May 19, 2006 |agency = Associated Press }}</ref> The show, entitled ''[[Toni Braxton: Revealed]]'', was to be performed six nights a week and was scheduled to run through to March 2007. Braxton later confirmed that she was extending her show through to August 2007. Due to its success, it was reported that Braxton would extend her show through to August 2008, though the show was later cancelled in order for Braxton to focus on her health after being diagnosed with [[microvascular angina]].<ref>{{cite news |last = Mascia |first = Kristen |title = Toni Braxton Cancels Vegas Show |url = http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20203349,00.html |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = People |date = May 30, 2008 }}</ref>

On January 12, 2007, Braxton filed a $10 million lawsuit against her former manager [[Barry Hankerson]], alleging "fraud, deception and double dealing", in addition to mismanaging her relationship with Arista Records.<ref name=tbmgr>{{cite news |last = Neumeister |first = Larry |title = Toni Braxton Sues Her Former Manager |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/12/AR2007011201814.html |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] |date = January 12, 2007 |agency = AP }}</ref> According to Braxton's lawsuit, Hankerson placed his personal financial interests ahead of hers by using 'double-talk' to compromise the relationship between Braxton and her former label, with Hankerson allegedly telling Arista that "Braxton no longer wanted to record for Arista," and telling Braxton that "Arista was not interested in working with her anymore".<ref name=tbmgr /> The suit was settled with Braxton being forced to return a $375,000 advance to Hankerson, who would also receive a percentage of the sales of her next album, and Hankerson releasing Braxton from her contract with him. The settlement also temporarily limited the companies with which Braxton could sign.<ref>{{cite news |title = Braxton Settles Lawsuit Against Ex-Manager |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1054986/braxton-settles-lawsuit-against-ex-manager |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = Billboard |date = February 14, 2007 |agency = AP }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070113/ap_on_en_mu/braxton_lawsuit_2 |title = Toni Braxton sues her former manager |access-date = January 12, 2007 |work = Yahoo |date = January 12, 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Hankerson claimed that the problems initially arose due to a number of disputes with Braxton and her wish to include her husband in her music.<ref>{{cite news |last = Finn |first = Natalie |title = Braxton Settles Up with Ex-Manager |url = http://au.eonline.com/news/54395/braxton-settles-up-with-ex-manager |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[E! Online]] |date = February 13, 2007 }}</ref>

=== 2008–2012: ''Pulse'' and television ===
Following the abrupt cancellation of her ''Toni Braxton: Revealed'' show, Braxton experienced financial difficulties when insurance agency [[Lloyd's of London]] refused to honor her policy that she purchased for upwards of $70,000 that included financial compensations for financial losses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton: My Insurance Co. Has No Heart|url=https://www.tmz.com/2009/04/29/toni-braxton-lawsuit|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=[[TMZ]]|date=April 29, 2009}}</ref><ref name="hinterlandgazette.com">{{cite news|last=Shan|first=Janet|title=Legal Briefs: Singer Toni Braxton Sues Lloyd's of London Over Cancelled Shoes|url=http://hinterlandgazette.com/2009/05/legal-briefs-singer-toni-braxton-sues.html|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=The Hinterland Gazette|date=May 3, 2009}}</ref><ref name="vh1.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/behind_the_music/episode.jhtml?episodeID=200331|title=Ep. 238 &#124; Toni Braxton &#124; Behind The Music|website=VH1.com|access-date=June 29, 2013}}</ref> Lloyd's responded with a counter-suit seeking damages against her because of an unrelated heart condition that the company was not made aware of at the time the application was filed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Insurance Co. Claims Braxton's a Hearty Liar|url=https://www.tmz.com/2009/10/01/lloyds-of-london-toni-braxton-lawsuit-heart-condition|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=TMZ|date=October 1, 2009}}</ref> While Braxton acknowledged that she did disclose her full medical history at the time,<ref name="hinterlandgazette.com"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hellobeautiful.com/509107/lloyds-of-london-sues-toni-braxton|title=Lloyds of London Sues Toni Braxton|website=Hellobeautiful.com|date=October 1, 2009|access-date=June 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/toni-braxton-sues-her-insurance-company/article/3816464|title=Toni Braxton sues her insurance company|website=Newsok.com|date=April 29, 2009|access-date=June 29, 2013}}</ref> she got on the hook for all damages because of the cancelled shows, being sued by multiple companies, and had to once again file for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton: My Vegas Show Broke Me|url=https://www.tmz.com/2010/10/07/toni-braxton-files-chapter-7-bankruptcy-las-vegas-show-broke-debt|access-date=December 2, 2013|newspaper=TMZ|date=October 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="vh1.com"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/07/06/toni-braxton-bankruptcy-case-settled|title=Toni Braxton – Bankruptcy Case finally settled|website=Tmz.com|date=June 7, 2013}}</ref> In September 2008, Braxton appeared on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of American dance competition series ''[[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''; her partner was [[Alec Mazo]]. They were voted off in the fifth week of the competition.<ref>{{Cite news |title = Announcing the Stars |url = http://abc.go.com/primetime/dancingwiththestars/index?pn=announcement |work = abc.go.com |year = 2008 |access-date = September 16, 2008 }}</ref>

[[File:Toni Braxton 2009 VH1 Divas.jpg|thumb|upright|Braxton at the ''[[VH1 Divas|VH1 Divas 2009]]'' red carpet]]
In 2009, Braxton signed to [[Atlantic Records]] and began work on her next studio album.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/listen_to_toni_braxtons_new_single_yesterday |title = Exclusive: Be the First to Listen to Toni Braxton's New Single 'Yesterday' |access-date = September 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090914055322/http://www.essence.com/news_entertainment/entertainment/articles/listen_to_toni_braxtons_new_single_yesterday |archive-date = September 14, 2009 }}</ref> In February 2010, she was part of the [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] Artists for Haiti who recorded "[[We Are the World 25 for Haiti]]", a remake of the 1985 hit "[[We Are the World]]", to help benefit the people of [[Haiti]] hollowing the [[moment magnitude scale|magnitude 7.0 M<sub>w</sub>]] [[2010 Haiti earthquake|earthquake]].<ref name="We Are the World 25">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/02/12/we-are-the-world-haiti-vi_n_461114.html |title=We Are The World, Haiti (VIDEO): New Version For Haiti Earthquake Victims |work=[[The Huffington Post|HuffingtonPost.com]] |publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc |date=February 12, 2010|access-date=May 24, 2020}}</ref> Three months later, ''[[Pulse (Toni Braxton album)|Pulse]]'', her seventh studio album, was released.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://thatgrapejuice.net/2010/01/toni-braxtons-pulse-pushed/ |title = Toni Braxton's 'Pulse' Pushed Back&nbsp;– Again &#124; ..::That Grape Juice // ThatGrapeJuice.net::.. &#124;&#124; Thirsty? |publisher = Thatgrapejuice.net |date = January 21, 2010 |access-date = November 12, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Praxis Media |url = http://www.radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_albums.htm |title = Radio1 Rodos Greece ::: UK Forthcoming Albums ::: Charts, DJ Promos, Dance, Lyrics, Free Mp3 Samples Downloads |publisher = Radio1.gr |access-date = November 12, 2010 }}</ref> A collection of up-tempo songs and R&B ballads with production varying from smooth to [[Electronic dance music|dance]]-based styles, it debuted at number nine on the US ''Billboard 200'', selling 54,000 copies in its first week, and topped the [[R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]], becoming Braxton's fifth US top-ten album. A moderate chart success elsewhere, it reached the top ten in Switzerland, and the top 20 in Germany and Greece. While critical reception of ''Pulse'' was generally positive,<ref name="Metacritic">[http://www.metacritic.com/music/pulse/toni-braxton/critic-reviews "Critic Reviews for Pulse"]. [[Metacritic]]. Retrieved on May 24, 2020.</ref> its singles "[[Yesterday (Toni Braxton song)|Yesterday]]", "[[Hands Tied]]" and "Make My Heart" achieved moderate chart success.<ref>{{cite web |author=Praxis Media |url=http://www.radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_singles.htm |title=Radio1 Rodos Greece ::: UK Forthcoming Singles ::: Charts, DJ Promos, Dance, Lyrics, Free Mp3 Samples Downloads |website=Radio1.gr |access-date=November 12, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122103050/http://radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_singles.htm |archive-date=November 22, 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.tonibraxton.com/news/hands-tied-make-my-heart-are-now-available-to-buy-exclusively-on-tonibraxtoncom/ |title = 'Hands Tied' & 'Make My Heart' Are Now Available To Buy Exclusively on ToniBraxton.com! – Blog Detail |publisher = ToniBraxton.com |date = January 29, 2010 |access-date = November 12, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110108182712/http://www.tonibraxton.com/news/hands-tied-make-my-heart-are-now-available-to-buy-exclusively-on-tonibraxtoncom/ |archive-date = January 8, 2011 }}</ref>

In 2011, Braxton signed with [[WE tv]] for a [[reality series]], ''[[Braxton Family Values]]''. Chronicling the lives of Braxton and her sisters [[Tamar Braxton|Tamar]], [[Traci Braxton|Traci]], Towanda, and [[Trina Braxton|Trina]], plus their mother Evelyn, the series debuted on April 12, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/04/wetv-toni-braxton-staten-island-cakes-tagline/ |title = WEtv unveils new details on Toni Braxton series, new cake series, and announces new tagline |author = James Hibberd |date = January 4, 2011 |access-date = April 16, 2011 }}</ref> It received favorable reviews from critics who recognized it as a "guilty pleasure" and spawned several seasons and spin-offs.<ref>{{cite press release|first=Amanda|last=Kondolojy|title=WE tv's 'Braxton Family Values' Closes Most-Watched Season Ever|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/09/10/we-tvs-braxton-family-values-closes-most-watched-season-ever/463014/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915025644/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/09/10/we-tvs-braxton-family-values-closes-most-watched-season-ever/463014/|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 15, 2015|work=TV by the Numbers|access-date=September 11, 2015|date=September 10, 2015|publisher=Tribune Digital Ventures}}</ref> In September 2011, Braxton parted ways with her long-time manager Vincent Herbert, husband of sister Tamar, and signed a new management deal with Los Angeles-based entertainment/production company The Collective.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://thatgrapejuice.net/2011/09/toni-braxton-signs-management/ |title = Toni Braxton Signs New Management Deal &#124; ..::That Grape Juice // ThatGrapeJuice.net::.. &#124;&#124; Thirsty? |publisher = Thatgrapejuice.net |date = September 6, 2011 |access-date = May 5, 2012 }}</ref> In March 2012, she released  the standalone single "[[I Heart You (Toni Braxton song)|I Heart You]]", a dance-pop, [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] and house song that peaked at number one on the US [[Dance Club Songs]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Pro Motion|url=http://blog.promotion-us.com/exclusive-mp3-toni-braxton-i-heart-you|title=Exclusive: Toni Braxton 'I Heart You'|website=Blog.promotion-us.com|date=March 9, 2012|access-date=April 9, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311172728/http://blog.promotion-us.com/exclusive-mp3-toni-braxton-i-heart-you|archive-date=March 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=toni braxton|chart=all}}</ref> Also that year, Braxton played Rosalie Rosebud, a singer with an over-the-top personality, in the children's musical adventure comedy film ''[[The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure]]'' alongside [[Jaime Pressly]] and [[Cloris Leachman]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/538/ms_impulsive/ |title = Toni Braxton interview by Pete Lewis, 'Blues & Soul' May 2010 |publisher = Bluesandsoul.com |access-date = January 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last = Moss |first = Ricki |url = http://www.bet.com/news/celebrities/2012/08/24/watch-toni-braxton-stars-in-childrens-film.html |title = Watch: Toni Braxton Stars in Children's Film &#124; News |publisher = BET |access-date = November 25, 2012 }}</ref> and began filming a lead role in the [[Lifetime Movie Network]] film ''[[Twist of Faith (2013 film)|Twist of Faith]]'' which premiered the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/387118/toni-braxton-retiring-from-music-to-focus-on-film-career|title=Toni Braxton Retiring From Music to Focus on Film Career|website=Eonline.com|date=February 11, 2013|access-date=February 17, 2013}}</ref>

===2013–2014: ''Love, Marriage and Divorce,'' Broadway return, and biographical film===
In 2013, Braxton and longtime creative music partner [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] began work on their collaborative studio album ''[[Love, Marriage & Divorce]]'' which was released in February 2014 under [[Motown Records]]. It received favorable reviews from music critics, who labeled it as "high-quality R&B",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raible|first1=Allan|title=Record Release Rundown: The Latest From Broken Bells, Toni Braxton & Babyface, Marissa Nadler and Mary Lambert|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/record-release-rundown-latest-broken-bells-toni-braxton/story?id=22417879#2|website=ABC News|publisher=ABC News|access-date=May 25, 2020}}</ref> and debuted at number 4 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and the top of the R&B/Hip-Hop Albums with first-week sales of 67,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Mendizabal|first=Amaya|title=Beyonce, Pharrell Williams Lead Mid-Year SoundScan R&B/Hip-Hop Charts|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6143270/beyonce-pharrell-williams-lead-mid-year-soundscan-rbhip-hop|access-date=May 25, 2020|date=July 2, 2014|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>  ''Love, Marriage & Divorce'' was nominated for World's Best Album at the [[2014 World Music Awards]] and won for [[Best R&B Album]] at the [[57th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees|title=The Official Site of Music's Biggest Night|website=Grammy.com|access-date=July 8, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201120225/http://www.grammy.com/nominees|archive-date=February 1, 2012}}</ref> Lead single "[[Hurt You (song)|Hurt You]]" reached number one on the US [[Adult R&B Songs]], becoming Braxton's first song to do so since her 2000 release "Just Be a Man About It".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2013-12-11/Toni-Braxton-and-Babyfaces-Hurt-You-Hits-No1-On-Two-Charts-Fantasia-Soars|title=Toni Braxton and Babyface's 'Hurt You' Hits No.1 on Two Charts|publisher=[[Singersroom]]|date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> The song also hit number 16 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Hot R&B/ Hip Hop Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/430180/toni-braxton/chart?f=364|title=Toni Braxton: Chart History|website=Billboard.com|access-date=February 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Toni Braxton – Chart history|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

In March 2014, Braxton, alongside Babyface, made her return to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in the musical ''[[After Midnight (musical)|After Midnight]]''. The third in rotation in the role of "Special Guest Star" following [[Fantasia Barrino]] and [[KD Lang]], they performed from March 18 to 31, 2014 at the [[Brooks Atkinson Theatre]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/toni-braxton-kenny-babyface-edmonds-636524|title=Toni Braxton and Kenny 'Babyface' Edmonds Join Broadway's 'After Midnight' Lineup|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 25, 2013|access-date=February 1, 2014|first=David|last=Rooney}}</ref> In May 2014, Braxton published a memoir, ''Unbreak My Heart: A Memoir'', through [[Harper Collins Publishers]]. In it, Braxton discusses her career success and struggles and the self-healing she took charge of after her own diagnosis with the auto-immune disease [[lupus]] and her son's diagnosis with autism.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/240653651.html |title=Toni Braxton memoir, 'Unbreak My Heart,' coming in May; to cover her hit songs, lupus |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |date=January 16, 2014 |access-date=February 1, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202115248/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/240653651.html |archive-date=February 2, 2014 }}</ref> In October 2015, Toni along with [[The Braxtons]] released the holiday album ''[[Braxton Family Christmas]]'' on [[Def Jam Recordings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2015/10/09/braxtons-are-releasing-christmas-album|title=Braxton Family Christmas|website=Essence.com|access-date=October 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.target.com/p/the-braxtons-braxton-family-christmas/-/A-50059014#prodSlot=medium_1_1&term=Braxton+Family+Christmas|title=The Braxtons – Braxton Family Christmas|website=Target.com|access-date=October 11, 2015}}</ref> Compromsing cover versions of Christmas standards and carols as well as several original songs, it debuted and peaked at number 27 on the US ''Billboard'' R&B/Hip-Hop Albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/388935/braxtons/chart?f=333|title=The Braxtons – Chart history|website=Billboard.com|date=October 5, 1996|access-date=December 7, 2015}}</ref>

In January 2016, Lifetime premiered the biographical film ''[[Toni Braxton: Unbreak My Heart]]'', based on Braxton's memoir.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/toni-braxton-life-story-lifetime-movie-unbreak-my-heart-1201528565|website=Deadline.com|date=September 15, 2015|access-date=September 15, 2015|title=Toni Braxton's Life Story Heading To Lifetime As Original Movie|first=Denise|last=Petski}}</ref> Actress [[Lex Scott Davis]] was cast to portray Braxton in the film. The biopic's premiere generated 3.6 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toni Braxton biopic earns high ratings|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/midnight-sun-blog/bal-toni-braxton-biopic-earns-high-ratings-story.html|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|access-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, Braxton announced that she would embark on a concert tour, titled [[The Hits Tour (Toni Braxton)|The Hits Tour]], in late 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=So excited to announce my new tour starting in October! Get your tickets now! Can't wait to see you all ❤️ •The Hits Tour•|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BITLo4GgvTu/|website=Instagram|publisher=Toni Braxton|access-date=July 25, 2016}} [https://bibliogram.pussthecat.org/p/BITLo4GgvTu Non-loginwalled link at bibliogram.pussthecat.org]</ref> On October 3, five days before the first date of the tour, Braxton was hospitalized due to complications with [[lupus]] resulting in canceling the first two dates of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=TONI BRAXTON HOSPITALIZED Birdman Rushes to Her Side|url=https://www.tmz.com/2016/10/03/toni-braxton-hospitalized-birdman/|website=Tmz.com|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Toni Braxton (Rescheduled from 10/8) Oakland Tickets – 1/28/17|url=http://www.vividseats.com/concerts/toni-braxton-tickets/toni-braxton-paramount-theatre-oakland-10-8-2109718.html|website=Vividseats.com|access-date=October 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 15, 2016, Braxton was admitted once again to hospital with complications with lupus, leading to another tour date cancellation, which was later rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web|title=TONI BRAXTON BACK IN HOSPITAL ... Postpones Show|url=https://www.tmz.com/2016/10/16/toni-braxton-hospital-postpones-show/|website=Tmz.com|access-date=October 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Toni Braxton Hospitalized Again With Lupus, Postpones Concert|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7542066/toni-braxton-hospitalized-lupus-postpones-concert|magazine=Billboard|access-date=October 16, 2016}}</ref> In December, Braxton announced that the January 2017 concert dates were canceled.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hey Guys, Unfortunately, Under doctor's recommendation, I'm going to have to cancel my shows in Oakland on January 28th and|url=https://twitter.com/tonibraxton/status/804483723957850112|website=Twitter|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles on January 29th, 2017. I'm feeling better and better every day and I want to be at my best when performing for you all.|url=https://twitter.com/tonibraxton/status/804483509410791424|website=Twitter|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I'm excited to say that I will be completing my new record this spring/summer of 2017 and can't wait to share it with you.|url=https://twitter.com/tonibraxton/status/804483598283898884|website=Twitter|date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stay tuned for more details. I look forward to seeing everyone back on tour in the summer of 2017!!!|url=https://twitter.com/tonibraxton/status/804483723957850112|website=Twitter|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref>

===2017–2019: ''Sex & Cigarettes'', touring, and other ventures===
In January 2018, Braxton starred in the Lifetime film ''Faith Under Fire''.<ref name="mylifetime">{{cite web|url=http://www.mylifetime.com/movies/faith-under-fire/about|title=About Faith Under Fire: The Antoinette Tuff Story – Lifetime|website=Mylifetime.com}}</ref> In March, her eighth studio album ''[[Sex & Cigarettes]]'', her first solo album in eight years, was released on Def Jam Recordings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toni Braxton Is Back On The Music Scene With 'Sex & Cigarettes'|url=https://hellobeautiful.com/2957549/toni-braxton-announces-new-album|access-date=September 8, 2017|date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> An adult contemporary R&B album with production from [[Fred Ball (producer)|Fred Ball]], Babyface, [[Dapo Torimiro]], and [[Tricky Stewart]], it debuted at number 22 on the US ''Billboard'' 200 and number one on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart. ''Sex & Cigarettes'' received mainly positive reviews from music critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex & Cigarettes by Toni Braxton Reviews and Tracks – Metacritic|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/sex-cigarettes/toni-braxton|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=May 25, 2020}}</ref> and was nominated for [[Best R&B Album]] at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Grammy2019">{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/61st-annual-grammy-awards|title=61st Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=December 6, 2018|website=Grammy.com|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> Second single "[[Long as I Live (Toni Braxton song)|Long as I Live]]" topped the US Adult R&B Songs, becoming Braxton's eighth chart topper, while breaking a tie with singers Maxwell and R. Kelly to give her sole possession of the second-most number-one's in the chart's 24-year history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Long As I Live – by Toni Braxton|website = [[iTunes]]|date = February 9, 2018|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/long-as-i-live-single/1342585144?l=en|access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> It also received Grammy Award nomination for [[Best R&B Performance]] and [[Best R&B Song]].<ref name="Grammy2019"/>

Also in 2018, Braxton and Uncle Bud's Hemp products created a joint marketing campaign for the latter's products, which Braxton noted as helpful in her battle against lupus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/toni-braxton-and-uncle-buds-natural-hemp-products-join-forces-300710241.html|title=Toni Braxton and Uncle Bud's Natural Hemp Products Join Forces|website=Prnewswire.com|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref> In April 2018, Braxton and her sisters Trina and Towanda appeared on their sister Traci's single "Broken Things".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tracibraxton.com/news|title=TraciBraxton – NEWS|website=Traci Braxton Reality Tv Celebrity|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> In November, Braxton and Towanda appeared in the holiday film ''Every Day is Christmas'', which premiered on Lifetime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9102152/|title=Every Day is Christmas|access-date=December 15, 2018|website=IMDb.com|date=November 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/15/lifetime-doubling-holiday-movies-2018/|title=Lifetime to double number of original holiday movies in 2018|website=Ew.com|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/lifetime-decks-its-halls-with-23-holiday-themed-movies-more-cheer-1202469310/|title=Lifetime Decks Its Halls With 23 Holiday-Themed Movies & More Cheer|first1=Erik|last1=Pedersen|date=September 24, 2018|website=Deadline.com|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/971199/all-the-lifetime-and-hallmark-holiday-movies-you-need-to-watch-this-year|title=Every Holiday Movie Coming to Lifetime and Hallmark This Fall|date=November 1, 2018|website=Eonline.com|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> The same month, she announced her [[As Long as I Live Tour]], a joint concert tour with [[SWV]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/entertainment/toni-braxton-and-swv-are-going-on-tour-next-year/|title=Yassss! Toni Braxton And SWV Are Going On Tour Next Year|first=Keyaira|last=Boone|website=Essence.com}}</ref> which took her to South Africa and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonibraxton.com/tour|title=Tour|website=Tonibraxton.com|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, Braxton headlined the 2019 Pittsburgh Pride festival.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.post-gazette.com/ae/music/2019/04/09/Toni-Braxton-Walk-the-Moon-will-headline-Pittsburgh-Pride-2019/stories/201904090096 |title = Toni Braxton, Walk the Moon will headline Pittsburgh Pride |last = Mervis |first = Scott |date = April 9, 2019 |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date = May 8, 2019 }}</ref>

===2020–present: New record label and ''Spell My Name''===
In April 2020, it was announced that Braxton had signed with [[Island Records]]. She released the single, "[[Do It (Toni Braxton song)|Do It]]", her first song under the new deal on April 6, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9351807/toni-braxton-signs-island-records-new-single-do-it-exclusive|title=Toni Braxton Signs with Island Records, Releases New Single 'Do It': Exclusive|website=Billboard.com|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> In May, Braxton released a remix EP for her second single "Dance".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7910612/toni-braxton-switches-it-up-with-dance-dave-aude-remix|title=Toni Braxton Switches It Up With "Dance (Dave Audé Remix)"|website=Idolator.com|date=May 15, 2020|access-date=May 15, 2020}}</ref> On June 26, 2020, [[Missy Elliott]] appeared on the official remix to the single "Do It".
Elliott co-produced the track alongside Hannon Lane.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/do-it-single/1519291115|title=Do It (Remix) featuring Missy Elliott|work=[[iTunes]]|date=June 26, 2020|access-date=June 28, 2020}}</ref> On August 4, 2020, Braxton released the music video for "Dance", directed by Mike Ho.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/08/toni-braxton-dance-single-music-video.html|title=Toni Braxton Misses Clubs As Much As the Rest of Us in 'Dance' Music Video|first=Justin|last=Curto|date=August 5, 2020|access-date=August 5, 2020}}</ref> On August 27, 2020, Braxton released the song "Nothin'".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@jay1341990/toni-braxton-nothin-lyrics-spell-my-name-c006df80b374|title=Toni Braxton — Nothin' Lyrics &#124;Spell My Name|date=August 28, 2020}}</ref> Braxton's tenth studio ''[[Spell My Name]]'' was released on August 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/spell-my-name/1525791171|title=Spell My Name by Toni Braxton|work=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=July 31, 2020}}</ref> On October 23, 2020, Braxton released a video for her song "Gotta Move On".<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/toni-braxton-her-gotta-move-on-video-1079587/|title = Toni Braxton Narrates Broken Relationship in 'Gotta Move On' Video|magazine = [[Rolling Stone]]|date = October 23, 2020}}</ref>

In 2021, Braxton competed on [[The Masked Singer (American season 6)|season six]] of ''[[The Masked Singer (American TV series)|The Masked Singer]]'' as "Pufferfish". She was the third to be eliminated during the two-night premiere alongside [[Dwight Howard]] as "Octopus" and [[Vivica A. Fox]] as "Mother Nature". Despite being unmasked, Braxton kept on a glittered KN95 [[cloth face mask]] over her mouth due to her lupus condition.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Masked Singer season 6 reveals: See every celebrity |url=https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-season-6-celebrity-reveals/ |access-date=February 19, 2022 |magazine=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> Braxton is an [[executive producer]] and star in the 2022 [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] movie  ''The Fallen Angels Murder Club''.<ref name="mylifetime-FAMC-ftdf">{{cite web |title=Watch: Fallen Angels Murder Club: Friends to Die For |url=https://www.mylifetime.com/movies/fallen-angels-murder-club-friends-to-die-for |website=[[Lifetime (TV network)]] |access-date=12 April 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-09-29|title=Toni Braxton headlining Lifetime multi-movie event|url=https://themusicuniverse.com/toni-braxton-headlining-lifetime-multi-movie-event/|access-date=2021-10-01|website=The Music Universe|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=White|first1=Peter|date=2021-09-27|title=Toni Braxton To Star In & EP Lifetime Multi-Movie Event 'The Fallen Angels Book Club' From Rhonda Baraka|url=https://deadline.com/2021/09/toni-braxton-lifetime-movies-the-fallen-angels-book-club-rhonda-baraka-1234845051/|access-date=2021-10-01|website=Deadline|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Artistry ==
Braxton has been recognized for her distinctive [[contralto]] voice.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://articles.courant.com/2012-03-24/entertainment/hc-toni-braxtons-concert-at-foxwoods-20120324_1_toni-braxton-angel-break-concert-review |title = Concert Review: Toni Braxton's Sultry Delivery Scores At Foxwoods |last = Kintner |first = Thomas |date = March 24, 2012 |publisher = courant.com |access-date = August 11, 2012 }}</ref><ref name="books.google.ca">{{Cite book |title = Rock-N-Roll Gold Rush |last = Dean |first = Maury |year = 2003 |publisher = Algora Publishing |isbn = 0-87586-207-1 |page = 34 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&q=whitney+houston&pg=PA87 |access-date = June 24, 2016 }}</ref> Her voice has been called "husky, sultry, elegant and sexy."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myplay.com/artists/toni-braxton |title=My Play: Toni Braxton |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015194514/http://myplay.com/artists/toni-braxton |archive-date=October 15, 2012 }}</ref> Due to the huskiness of her voice, Braxton often used male singers such as [[Michael McDonald (singer)|Michael McDonald]], [[Luther Vandross]] and [[Stevie Wonder]] as vocal style models.<ref name=stevehuey>{{cite web |last = Huey |first = Steve |url = https://www.allmusic.com/artist/toni-braxton-mn0000935330 |title = Toni Braxton&nbsp;– Music Biography, Credits and Discography |website = AllMusic |access-date = July 29, 2012 }}</ref> [[Chaka Khan]] and [[Anita Baker]] were two of the few female singers that she could stylize. Steve Huey of [[AllMusic]] cites a key to Braxton's success is the versatility of her voice, which he states as being "soulful enough for [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] audiences, but smooth enough for adult contemporary; sophisticated enough for adults, but sultry enough for younger listeners; strong enough in the face of heartbreak to appeal to women, but ravishing enough to nab the fellas."<ref name=stevehuey/>

Braxton began her career singing traditional R&B and soft rock ballads and love songs on her debut and second albums. However, [[hip-hop soul]] and [[dance music]] elements begun to get spun into her sound on ''The Heat'',<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-heat-mw0000256509 |title = The Heat Review |website = [[AllMusic]] |access-date = July 8, 2015 }}</ref> ''More Than a Woman'',<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/more-than-a-woman-mw0000224666 |title = More Than A Woman |website = [[AllMusic]] |access-date = July 8, 2015 }}</ref> and ''Pulse''. She also showcased her classical training while performing in Broadway plays ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' and ''[[Aida]]'' as well as her duet with [[Il Divo]], "The Time of Our Lives".

== Legacy ==
Toni Braxton became an R&B superstar after the release of her first album. LA Reid stated during an interview with [[VH1]]: "We called her the first lady of LaFace. She was our Diva. [[Clive Davis|Clive]] had [[Whitney Houston|Whitney]], [[Tommy Mottola|Tommy]] had [[Mariah Carey|Mariah]] and we had Toni." BBC called the album "spiritedly, mature soul at its best – and just urban enough to make it the bedroom album for the hip hop generation."<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/j4fd |title = Music – Review of Toni Braxton – Toni Braxton |publisher = BBC |date = July 13, 1993 |access-date = February 1, 2014 }}</ref> Over the span of her career Braxton has sold over 70 million records,{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} including 40 million albums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonibraxton.com/bio/ |title=Toni Braxton Bio |publisher=Toni Braxton Official Website |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727061235/http://www.tonibraxton.com/bio/ |archive-date=July 27, 2014 }}</ref> worldwide. Her hit "[[Un-Break My Heart]]", the [[Diane Warren]]-penned ballad, spent 11-weeks at number 1. Bob McCann, author of ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television'' (2010), considered it "simply one of the most haunting R&B records ever made." Reviewer Mark Edward Nero named it one of the best R&B break-up songs and considered it Braxton's "finest moment". He further commented, "damn, this song is so sad it can make people cry for hours at a time."  Braxton is a recipient of seven [[Grammy Award]]s, seven [[American Music Awards]], and nine [[Billboard Music Awards]].{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} She has been cited as an influence by various artists, such as [[Beyoncé]], sister [[Tamar Braxton]], [[Billie Godfrey]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Leela James]], [[Keyshia Cole]], [[Teyana Taylor]], [[Kehlani]] and [[Anja Nissen]].<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8482487/beyonce-toni-braxton-halloween-costume |title = Beyonce Pays Tribute to Toni Braxton With Spot-On 'Phoni Braxton' Halloween Costume |publisher = Billboard |date = October 30, 2018 |access-date = May 7, 2020 }}</ref>

Braxton's career, she made several impacts on fashion, mostly for her high splits in her dresses. In 2011, Braxton topped the list for the [[Grammy Award]]'s best dressed of the decade.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/grammy-fashion-the-best-and-worst-of-the-decade/ |title = Grammy Fashion: The Best and Worst of the Decade |publisher = CBS News |date = February 10, 2011 |access-date = February 1, 2014 }}</ref> "I've always gone a little risque with all my other award show outfits."<ref>{{cite magazine |url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/racy-grammy-dresses-419267#2-toni-braxton |title = Racy Grammy Dresses |magazine = Hollywood Reporter |date = February 8, 2013 |access-date = February 1, 2014 |first = Emily |last = Helwig }}</ref> In 2012, Braxton made the list for [[VH1]]'s 50 Greatest Women in Music. Braxton's 2000 performance at [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] is ranked as one of the most memorable Super Bowl performances.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/02/the-super-bowl-top-5-memorable-halftime-shows/ |title = The Super Bowl: Top 5 Memorable Halftime Shows – ABC News |publisher = Abcnews.go.com |date = February 3, 2012 |access-date = February 1, 2014 }}</ref> Braxton is featured alongside other R&B and pop divas as a primary character on the popular [[web series|web]] [[parody]] ''[[Got 2B Real: The Diva Variety Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Glazer|first=Eliot|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/01/got-2-b-real.html|title=Behold the Newest Installment of 'Got 2 B Real,' a Web Series That Dubs Over the Voices of R&B Goddesses|website=Vulture.com}}</ref> With her Las Vegas residency ''Toni Braxton: Revealed'', she became the first African American performer in Las Vegas to have her act enter the top ten Vegas shows charting.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Braxton also made headlines for her Giantto Million Dollar Microphone that she performed every show with. Braxton said: "I think it's a great element to the show. You have to have a little sprinkle of [[Liberace]] and this is my little sprinkle of that." Braxton's prop was made up of white gold and encrusted with 650 karats of diamonds.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.tmz.com/2006/09/01/braxtons-million-dollar-baby/ |title = Braxton's Million Dollar Baby |website=Tmz.com |date = January 9, 2006 |access-date = February 1, 2014 }}</ref> The microphone reportedly cost $1 million.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

Braxton has also been seen as a [[gay icon]], with some of her songs becoming [[gay anthem]]s, such as "[[Un-Break My Heart]]", "[[He Wasn't Man Enough]]" and "[[Make My Heart]]". The singer stated that after the release of "Un-Break My Heart", she "recognized all the support. And it was really wonderful." When asked about her gay fans, Braxton said "I love my boys because my boys help me be a better girl. My choreographer and my video director are gay, and they’ve been my best friends since I started in the industry. They’re my favorite part of the whole industry".<ref>{{cite web |url = https://pridesource.com/article/41248/ |title = Toni Braxton finds her 'Pulse' |publisher = pridesource.com |date = May 6, 2010 |access-date = May 7, 2020 }}</ref>

== Personal life ==
===Relationships===
Braxton met musician [[Keri Lewis]] when his group, [[Mint Condition]], opened for her on tour; they married on April 21, 2001. In December 2001, she gave birth to their first child, a son named Denim Cole Braxton-Lewis. In 2002, while gearing up for the release of her fourth studio album, Braxton discovered she was pregnant with her second child; the complicated pregnancy confined her to [[bed rest]]. The couple's second son, Diezel Ky Braxton-Lewis, was born in March 2003. As Diezel has been diagnosed with [[autism]], Braxton has become involved with [[Autism Speaks]], serving as their International Spokesperson. In November 2009 Braxton announced that she and her husband had separated. The couple later divorced in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web |author = Zach Johnson |url = http://m.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/toni-braxton-finalizes-divorce-from-keri-lewis-2013257/ |title = Toni Braxton Finalizes Divorce From Keri Lewis |publisher = usmagazine.com |date = July 25, 2013 |access-date = July 10, 2015 }}</ref>

In her early 30s, Braxton had an abortion after discovering she was pregnant by then-boyfriend Keri Lewis. In her memoir ''Unbreak my Heart'', Braxton discusses her abortion and guilt, saying that her son Diezel's autism was "God's payback".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/05/toni-braxton-thinks-god-punished-her-for-getting-an-abortion-by-giving-her-son-autism/371518/|title=Toni Braxton Thinks God Punished Her for Getting an Abortion by Giving Her Son Autism|last=Jones|first=Allie|date=May 23, 2014|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> 
In an October 2006 concert at the [[Flamingo Las Vegas]], Braxton broke down in tears while announcing to the audience that just before the concert began she had been told that her son, Diezel, had been diagnosed with [[autism]].<ref>{{cite news |last = Walls |first = Jeannette |title = O.J. Simpson to confess – hypothetically, Plus: Toni Braxton sobs while discussing autistic son |url = http://www.today.com/id/15066202 |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[Today.com]] |date = October 30, 2006 }}</ref> Braxton has been outspoken regarding her doctor's failure to diagnose Diezel's condition earlier, contending that if he had been diagnosed earlier he could have received treatment earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title = Braxton Upset With Doctor's Over Son's Autism |url = http://www.contactmusic.com/news/braxton-upset-with-doctors-over-sons-autism_1009575 |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[Contactmusic.com]] |date = September 29, 2006 }}</ref> As well as becoming a spokeswoman for [[Autism Speaks]],<ref>{{cite news |title = Toni Braxton Named National Celebrity Spokesperson for Autism Speaks |url = http://www.autismspeaks.org/about-us/press-releases/toni-braxton-named-national-celebrity-spokesperson-autism-speaks |access-date = December 2, 2013 |newspaper = [[Autism Speaks]] |date = March 7, 2007 }}</ref> she is also a spokeswoman for the [[American Heart Association]].

On July 8, 2015, Braxton's attorney, Antavius Weems, announced that Braxton had settled her contentious child support case with her former husband, Keri Lewis.<ref>{{cite web |author = Ny Magee |url = http://www.eurweb.com/2015/07/toni-braxton-settles-child-support-battle-with-ex-husband/ |title = Toni Braxton Settles Child Support Battle with Ex-husband |publisher = eurweb.com |date = July 8, 2015 |access-date = July 10, 2015 }}</ref> On June 2, 2016, the city and county officials of [[Atlanta, Georgia]], named June 2 as Toni Braxton Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raycornelius.com/2016/06/toni-braxton-honored-with-atls-phoenix-award-and-more-photos/|title=Toni Braxton honored with ATL's Phoenix Award and more! [PHOTOS]|website=Raycornelius.com|language=en-US|access-date=December 17, 2017}}</ref>

Braxton began dating rapper [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] in May 2016, and the couple announced their engagement in February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/uk/news/914842/toni-braxton-confirms-engagement-to-birdman-see-her-massive-ring|title=Toni Braxton Confirms Engagement to Birdman: See Her Massive Ring|website=Eonline.com|date=February 19, 2018|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, the couple called off the engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2019-01-02-toni-braxton-birdman-call-of-engagement-its-over/|title=Toni Braxton & Birdman Call Off Engagement: 'It's Over'|last=Blakemore|first=Peyton|work=[[iHeartRadio]]|date=January 2, 2019|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> However, in April 2019, both Braxton and Birdman confirmed that they were still together.<ref>{{cite web |author = Danilo Castro |url = https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/04/toni-braxton-fiance-birdman-still-together/ |title = Are Toni Braxton & Fiance Birdman Still Together? |date= April 11, 2019 }}</ref>

=== Health problems ===
In August 2007, rumors surfaced that Braxton had been diagnosed with breast cancer. She stated to ''[[Access Hollywood]]'' that the breast cancer rumors were false and that her health was very good. However, in 2008, she had a [[Benign tumor|benign]] lump removed from her breast. On April 8, 2008, near the end of her two-year run at the [[Flamingo Hotel]], Braxton was briefly hospitalized and the remaining dates on the show, which was scheduled to end on August 23, 2008, were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.huliq.com/57437/toni-braxton-cancels-more-shows-due-unidentified-illness |access-date = January 23, 2016 |work = Huliq |title = Toni Braxton Cancels More Shows Due to Unidentified Illness |date = April 21, 2008 }}</ref> Later, while appearing on Season 7 of ''Dancing with the Stars'', she stated, that she has been diagnosed with [[Microangiopathy|microvascular angina]] (small vessel disease).<ref>{{cite web |url = https://abcnews.go.com/Health/HeartDiseaseNews/story?id=5870125 |access-date = January 23, 2016 |date = September 24, 2008 |work = [[ABC News]] |publisher = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |first = Radha |last = Chitale |title = Dancing Won't Un-Break Toni Braxton's Heart }}</ref>

On November 18, 2010, Braxton revealed to [[CBS News]] that she had been diagnosed with [[systemic lupus erythematosus]] (SLE), a potentially life-threatening autoimmune disease.<ref name="Lupus">{{cite web|url=http://heal-good.blogspot.com/2014/02/toni-braxton-is-fighter-of-lupus.html|access-date=January 23, 2016|work=Heal Good|title=Toni Braxton is a fighter of Lupus}}</ref>

Braxton's uncle died of complications from lupus.<ref name="Lupus"/> While taping her reality series ''[[Braxton Family Values]]'', she went into hospital for surgery. Braxton was hospitalized in Los Angeles in December 2012 because of "minor health issues" related to [[lupus]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481514/toni-braxton-hospitalized-for-lupus-related-health-issues|access-date=January 23, 2016|date=December 8, 2012|agency=Associated Press|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=Toni Braxton Hospitalized for Lupus-Related Health Issues}}</ref>

